+{"parentUuid":"c958eaa2-2da2-43c0-b7e1-88fe5c49b920","isSidechain":false,"userType":"external","cwd":"/workspace","sessionId":"401085df-6b68-45f0-a619-bb2edaeed278","version":"2.1.63","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"async-strolling-kite","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_014kTFE3vZNg9PaEyiDgNXfK","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture of all the bugs. Let me analyze each one:\n\n**Bug 1: EventBus uses global handlers (module-level)**\nThe `globalHandlers` map in `bus.ts` is module-level, meaning handlers persist across tests. Each test creates a `new EventBus()` and calls `registerHandlers()`, but the old handlers from previous tests remain. The `clear()` method exists but it's never called in `beforeEach`. Actually wait - looking at the tests, the inventory test's `beforeEach` creates a new EventBus and registers handlers. But since `globalHandlers` is module-level, all handlers accumulate across tests. \n\nThe test failures showing \"Insufficient stock\" even with stock set to 10 or 20 make sense now—when multiple CREATED events fire, they're triggering accumulated handlers from previous tests, causing the stock calculations to go wrong. Since each test creates a new EventBus instance but they all share the same module-level `globalHandlers` map, handlers keep piling up without being cleared between tests. Looking at this test more carefully, by the time it runs as the 4th test, `registerHandlers()` has been called four times in beforeEach, so there are four instances of `handleOrderCreated` registered in the global handlers map. When the event fires, all four handlers execute, and the first one from test 1's service fails because that repo has no stock set, throwing \"Insufficient stock\". This confirms the root cause: EventBus stores handlers at the module level and never clears them between tests, so handlers from previous tests keep running. The fix is to make handlers instance-level instead of global. Now I'm looking at the second bug around line 38 in OrderRepository.update().\n\nThe update method is replacing the entire order object with just the updates plus id and timestamp, when it should be merging the updates into the existing order to preserve fields like customerId, notes, items, and total. That's why the \"updates order preserves other fields\" test fails—after updating with just `{ status: 'confirmed' }`, all the other fields get wiped out. This also cascades into the `cancelOrder` failures where items becomes undefined after the order is updated, causing the `.map()` call to crash.\n\nThe third bug is in BillingService where `handleRefund` isn't bound to `this`... I'm walking through the calculation step by step to understand why the test expects 130.86 instead of 130.87. The issue is that the current code rounds intermediate values separately, but the test expects the calculation to preserve more precision until the final rounding—using 118.966 as the after-discount amount rather than 118.97, which then gives a tax of 11.8966 and a final total of 130.8626 that rounds down to 130.86. So the test expects the calculation WITHOUT intermediate rounding. The current code rounds at each intermediate step, but the test expects NO intermediate rounding - just round the final total. Let me re-check:\n\nWithout intermediate rounding:\n- subtotal = 139.96\n- discountAmount = 139.96 * 0.15 = 20.994\n- afterDiscount = 139.96 - 20.994 = 118.966\n- tax = 118.966 * 0.1 = 11.8966\n- total = 118.966 + 11.8966 = 130.8626 → round to 130.86\n\nWith intermediate rounding:\n- discountAmount = round(20.994) = 20.99\n- afterDiscount = round(118.97) = 118.97\n- taxAmount = round(11.897) = 11.90\n- total = 130.87\n\nSo the fix is to NOT round intermediate values, only round the final outputs. Now I'm checking the other test cases to confirm this approach works across the board. Test 1 and 2 pass either way, but Test 4 with the penny-edge case shows the real difference: without intermediate rounding I get 33.88, but rounding at each step gives a different result.\n\nNow I'm looking at the next bug - there's an issue with the refund window check in OrderService.\n\nrefundOrder. The test expects a refund to succeed on exactly day 30, but the `>=` operator rejects it. However, there's a deeper problem: the test also fails because the order object loses all its fields when the repository's update method doesn't properly merge changes. When the test updates just the createdAt timestamp, the order's status becomes undefined, which causes the subsequent cancelOrder call to fail before it even reaches the refund window check.\n\nOnce the repository merge bug is fixed, the status will be preserved and cancelOrder will work. Then refundOrder will hit the actual bug: the `>=` comparison should be `>` to allow refunds on exactly day 30.\n\nNow I'm looking at another issue in the InventoryService. When cancelOrder emits a CANCELLED event, it doesn't include a status field in the event payload, but the inventory service is checking for `eventWithItems.status !== 'cancelled'` to decide whether to process the cancellation.\n\nThe inventory test manually includes the status field when emitting the event, so it passes. But when going through the actual order service flow, the status field is missing from the emitted event, causing the inventory service to skip stock release. I need to either remove that status check from the inventory service or add the status field to the event emission.\n\nLooking at the order service's cancelOrder method, it's not including `status: 'cancelled'` in the event payload. That's the fix—I'll add that field to match what the inventory service expects.\n\nNow I'm compiling the complete list of bugs I've identified: the EventBus needs instance-level handlers instead of global ones, OrderRepository.update needs to preserve existing fields when merging updates, BillingService's refund handler needs proper binding, the billing calculator should only round final totals not intermediate values, the refund eligibility check should use `>` instead of `>=`, and the order cancellation event needs the status field added.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":7498,"cache_read_input_tokens":32366,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":7498,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"}},"requestId":"req_011CYuhviUWozWFvpW8BTtk6","type":"assistant","uuid":"200c5632-3573-4a3c-99e1-2bf14bb0e993","timestamp":"2026-03-10T16:22:50.693Z"}
